Synchronous programming is a traditional approach in which the execution of a function waits for the completion of all sub-functions or operations before moving on to the next step. This means that the program will wait for the response from a function call before proceeding with the next line of code. 

Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, is an event-driven approach in which functions can execute independently and concurrently without waiting for each other's completion. In this model, the execution of a program continues while tasks are being processed asynchronously. This allows multiple operations to be carried out simultaneously, improving overall performance and responsiveness.

Here is an example of synchronous programming in JavaScript:
```javascript
function getWeather(city) {
  let weatherData = fetchWeatherData(city);
  return processWeatherData(weatherData);
}

getWeather("Tokyo").then((result) => console.log(result));
```
In this example, the `getWeather` function first calls `fetchWeatherData`, which retrieves weather data for the given city. Then, it processes that data using `processWeatherData`. The entire function will not continue until the asynchronous call to `fetchWeatherData` has completed and returned a result.

Here is an example of asynchronous programming in JavaScript:
```javascript
function getWeather(city) {
  fetchWeatherData(city).then((weatherData) => processWeatherData(weatherData));
}

getWeather("Tokyo").then((result) => console.log(result));
```
In this example, the `getWeather` function immediately calls `fetchWeatherData`, which retrieves weather data for the given city asynchronously. It then passes the returned data to another asynchronous function call, `processWeatherData`. The entire function will continue even though both of these functions are still in progress.

This example demonstrates how an asynchronous function can be used to make a program more responsive and improve its overall performance by executing tasks concurrently.

